This test was expecting null to be returned from the getIndexes call. Now, an empty collection is returned.

I made the changes to disjointRegionsAndGroupsFailsToDefineIndexes below, and the test is now passing. Can you apply them to your branch and resubmit the PR?
```
  VMProvider.invokeInEveryMember(() -> {
	  Cache cache = ClusterStartupRule.getCache();
	  QueryService queryService = cache.getQueryService();
	  Region region1 = cache.getRegion(region1Name);

-   // Returns null instead of an empty collection if there are no indexes...
-   assertThat(queryService.getIndexes(region1)).isNull();
+   assertThat(queryService.getIndexes(region1)).isEmpty();
  }, server1, server2);

  VMProvider.invokeInEveryMember(() -> {
	  Cache cache = ClusterStartupRule.getCache();
	  QueryService queryService = cache.getQueryService();
	  Region region2 = cache.getRegion(region2Name);

-   assertThat(queryService.getIndexes(region2)).isNull();
+   assertThat(queryService.getIndexes(region2)).isEmpty();
  }, server3);
```

@mcmellawatt Ooo, good catch.  I hate it when I come across that sort of stuff.

Also, weird GitHub error.

[edit:] Oh, you might have been looking at only the first commit?  I ended up reverting those changes as they creeped out in scope.  Maybe it was trying to tag the HEAD changes, but after they squash there weren't any.

I found the cause. The 1st lines are the datastores creating cache + regions async. This should be synchronous:
```java
    vm1.invoke(() -> createColocatedRegions(vm1));
    vm2.invoke(() -> createColocatedRegions(vm2));

    vm0.invoke(() -> createAccessor());
```

Rather than adding a task per category let's add a category project property that can be used in each of the primary test tasks (unit, integration, etc.).
@sboorlagadda 
```
if (project.hasProperty("testCategory")) {
  useJUnit {
     includeCategories+= project.testCategory
   }
 }
```

then on the command line you will run:
`./gradlew test -PtestCategory=org.apache.geode.test.junit.categories.GfshTest`
will run all unit tests in this category
or
`./gradlew test integrationTest -PtestCategory=org.apache.geode.test.junit.categories.GfshTest`
will runn all unit and integration tests in this category.

This way every time someone adds a new category gradle isn't mucked with.
